objections.suggested_fix:
Invert the logic: instead of a catch-all with a denylist, mount the SPA fallback explicitly. Option A: Use a middleware that checks if the request path has a file extension or matches a known backend prefix set, and only falls through to SPA for 'clean' paths. Option B (simpler): Register a `@app.exception_handler(404)` that returns index.html only for `text/html` Accept headers (browser navigation), not for API consumers. This also correctly handles programmatic fetch requests that hit unknown paths. Example:

```python
from starlette.exceptions import HTTPException as StarletteHTTPException

@app.exception_handler(StarletteHTTPException)
async def spa_404_handler(request, exc):
    if exc.status_code == 404 and 'text/html' in request.headers.get('accept', ''):
        return FileResponse('src/frontend/web/dist/index.html', headers={'Cache-Control': 'no-cache'})
    return JSONResponse({'detail': exc.detail}, status_code=exc.status_code)
```

Define api.js contract explicitly:

```javascript
// api.js
const API_BASE = '/api';

class ApiError extends Error {
  constructor(status, body) {
    super(`API ${status}: ${body?.detail || 'Unknown error'}`);
    this.status = status;
    this.body = body;
  }
}

async function request(path, { signal, params, method = 'GET', body } = {}) {
  const url = new URL(`${API_BASE}${path}`, window.location.origin);
  if (params) Object.entries(params).forEach(([k, v]) => url.searchParams.set(k, v));

  const res = await fetch(url, {
    method,
    signal,
    headers: body ? { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' } : undefined,
    body: body ? JSON.stringify(body) : undefined,
  });

  if (!res.ok) {
    const errBody = await res.json().catch(() => null);
    throw new ApiError(res.status, errBody);
  }
  return res.json();
}
```

Also define the `useAsync` or `DataView` loading/error/success/empty state pattern explicitly, since `DataView.jsx` is listed but undocumented.

Define DataView contract:

```jsx
// DataView renders exactly one of four states.
// No intermediate states, no partial renders.
function DataView({ status, data, error, skeleton, empty, children }) {
  switch (status) {
    case 'loading': return skeleton;
    case 'error': return <ErrorState error={error} onRetry={...} />;
    case 'empty': return empty || <EmptyState />;
    case 'success': return children(data);
    default: throw new Error(`Unknown DataView status: ${status}`);
  }
}
```

Also specify the ScreenSkeleton variants тАФ what structural shapes do they render? Cards? Lines? Timeline nodes? This directly affects perceived performance.

Move the `<meta name="theme-color" content="#0A0A0B">` ABOVE the inline script, or use a null check:
```javascript
var m = document.querySelector('meta[name="theme-color"]');
if (m) m.content = t === 'dark' ? '#0A0A0B' : '#FFFFFF';
